WEBVTT

00:00:08.920 --> 00:00:14.480
So I'd like to bring up a good friend,
long-time associate, Jim Batson,

00:00:14.520 --> 00:00:16.600
QuickTime team, one of the founding
members of QuickTime team.

00:00:16.600 --> 00:00:18.300
He's going to help me
with some of the demos.

00:00:18.300 --> 00:00:21.210
You know him well.

00:00:25.490 --> 00:00:34.920
So, QuickTime has had one of the
best reputations in the industry

00:00:35.400 --> 00:00:37.400
when it comes to the quality
of the software we produce.

00:00:37.400 --> 00:00:40.360
And I am really proud of this.

00:00:40.470 --> 00:00:43.400
This is something we've worked really,
really hard on over the years.

00:00:43.400 --> 00:00:47.690
And a big part of the way that
we accomplished that is through a

00:00:47.690 --> 00:00:50.310
very aggressive seeding program.

00:00:50.400 --> 00:00:54.370
Now, somewhere along the way
in the last few months,

00:00:54.490 --> 00:00:56.560
in the frenzy of all this
stuff we've been doing,

00:00:56.600 --> 00:00:58.300
we seem to drop the ball.

00:00:58.400 --> 00:01:01.510
And a couple of releases,
a QuickTime got out the

00:01:01.510 --> 00:01:03.230
door without any seeding.

00:01:03.400 --> 00:01:06.400
And you guys, you're very passionate.

00:01:06.400 --> 00:01:09.400
You let us know really clearly and
frankly how you feel about that.

00:01:11.220 --> 00:01:15.400
So we decided to make a
movie to commemorate this,

00:01:15.400 --> 00:01:18.750
learning these old hard
lessons all over again,

00:01:18.750 --> 00:01:21.010
and we'd like to show that to you now.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:30.440
I'm done programming for today.

00:01:30.440 --> 00:01:33.000
I think I'll relax
with some QuickTime TV.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:34.000
I've got kickboxing.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:36.280
I've got some...ah!

00:01:36.280 --> 00:01:37.000
Let's do it.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:39.620
QuickTime!

00:01:39.620 --> 00:01:39.620
Green is hip!

00:01:39.620 --> 00:01:39.620
Kick!

00:01:53.040 --> 00:01:54.080
Hey Jim!

00:01:54.080 --> 00:01:55.390
What is it this time?

00:01:55.450 --> 00:01:59.600
I just updated a QuickTime 4.1.1
and it broke my website!

00:01:59.600 --> 00:02:00.880
Yeah, right.

00:02:00.920 --> 00:02:04.880
Yeah,
well what are you going to do about it?

00:02:04.880 --> 00:02:05.400
Whatever.

00:03:23.600 --> 00:03:25.770
This one has a little star.

00:03:25.770 --> 00:03:27.100
This one has a little car.

00:03:27.100 --> 00:03:29.860
Say, what a lot of seeds there are.

00:03:32.500 --> 00:03:35.540
Yes, some are red and some are blue.

00:03:35.540 --> 00:03:38.060
Some are old and some are new.

00:04:50.650 --> 00:04:52.670
One of the great things about being
on the QuickTime team is there

00:04:52.700 --> 00:04:53.600
are some really creative people.

00:04:53.600 --> 00:04:55.480
We've got some good editors.

00:04:55.770 --> 00:04:57.270
It's a lot of fun.

00:04:57.310 --> 00:04:57.310
It's really a ride.

00:04:58.390 --> 00:05:05.300
So, may we not forget this hard
lesson for another nine years.

00:05:05.300 --> 00:05:08.150
Can we go back to slides, please?

00:05:11.050 --> 00:05:16.000
So, you're probably interested in how
you can get involved in seeding.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:19.260
We have decided to make some
changes in the way we're doing our

00:05:19.410 --> 00:05:22.440
seeding to make it easier to reach
more of you more efficiently,

00:05:22.440 --> 00:05:24.000
more effectively.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:27.990
And effective immediately,
we're moving the whole seeding program

00:05:28.130 --> 00:05:32.460
for QuickTime over to be in line with
the regular Apple seeding that is done

00:05:32.460 --> 00:05:34.790
elsewhere in the company these days.

00:05:35.170 --> 00:05:39.150
The easiest thing for you to do is
to go up to the developer website,

00:05:39.180 --> 00:05:42.000
and you can get the details,
you can sign up,

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:43.000
it's not going to cost you anything.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:48.600
And we've also got these mailing lists,
you can find them at list.apple.com,

00:05:48.600 --> 00:05:51.000
there's about a half a dozen of them.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:55.560
And you can find out what's going on,
how your other peer developers

00:05:55.560 --> 00:05:57.970
are doing with the various seeds.

00:05:58.010 --> 00:06:03.790
And it should be a good forum to
make a great product going forward.

00:06:05.290 --> 00:06:08.490
The guy who's going to keep us honest
in all this is a guy named Jeff Lowe.

00:06:08.490 --> 00:06:11.560
He's the QuickTime technology
manager here at Apple.

00:06:11.640 --> 00:06:14.700
And so if you have any
questions or issues or concerns,

00:06:14.830 --> 00:06:18.750
feel free to send him an email,
and he'll get right back to you.

00:06:19.500 --> 00:06:24.150
So, this show seems to be about Mac OS X.

00:06:24.490 --> 00:06:28.740
You've seen a lot of QuickTime in
the keynote session this morning.

00:06:29.200 --> 00:06:31.840
Unfortunately, you're probably not going
to see a lot of QuickTime,

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:35.100
a lot of Mac OS X in this session.

00:06:35.360 --> 00:06:40.480
The basic message I want to bring to you
today is that QuickTime and Mac OS X is

00:06:40.560 --> 00:06:42.580
really like QuickTime everywhere else.

00:06:42.590 --> 00:06:46.760
We've got the same APIs,
the same features, the same bugs,

00:06:46.860 --> 00:06:50.240
it's all the same stuff.

00:06:50.260 --> 00:06:51.600
It's all there in DP4.

00:06:51.880 --> 00:06:52.710
You've got the disks.

00:06:52.870 --> 00:06:54.640
You know,
I encourage you to go and play with

00:06:54.640 --> 00:06:56.640
it and let us know what you think.

00:06:56.640 --> 00:06:59.130
We're going to be working on
it throughout the rest of the

00:06:59.130 --> 00:07:02.820
summer as we wrap this up,
and hopefully come fall we'll

00:07:02.820 --> 00:07:05.740
have a great piece of software
there that you can base your

00:07:05.740 --> 00:07:07.220
applications on Mac OS X on.

00:07:09.500 --> 00:07:13.100
So we've got only one
session focused on Mac OS X,

00:07:13.100 --> 00:07:17.460
and I will confess that that session
isn't entirely about Mac OS X.

00:07:17.800 --> 00:07:20.590
But the reality is there's just
not that much that you need to know

00:07:20.610 --> 00:07:24.500
about Mac OS X for QuickTime on X.

00:07:26.300 --> 00:07:28.290
So, okay,
let's talk about some of the details

00:07:28.290 --> 00:07:31.140
in the QuickTime technology area,
a little bit about what we've been

00:07:31.190 --> 00:07:34.200
doing over the last year since
we got a chance to get together.

00:07:34.200 --> 00:07:38.080
One of the key areas that we
are focused on with QuickTime is

00:07:38.080 --> 00:07:40.160
an area of content creation.

00:07:40.250 --> 00:07:44.200
Of course, Apple Computer is completely
focused on content creation.

00:07:44.200 --> 00:07:45.510
These are our customers.

00:07:45.680 --> 00:07:49.420
These are our core customers,
creative people working in education,

00:07:49.420 --> 00:07:51.730
consumers,
design and publishing professionals

00:07:52.390 --> 00:07:54.100
who create content for a living.

00:07:54.200 --> 00:07:57.510
We are doing innovative
work in a number of areas,

00:07:57.630 --> 00:08:01.270
and the first one I want to
talk about is Sound Manager.

00:08:01.350 --> 00:08:02.200
Ah, see, I lied.

00:08:02.200 --> 00:08:06.130
I'm going to talk a little
bit more about Mac OS X.

00:08:06.400 --> 00:08:09.300
The sound manager on Mac OS X is
getting a major facelift,

00:08:09.300 --> 00:08:12.980
and we're adding some key
capabilities that developers in

00:08:12.980 --> 00:08:17.430
the professional audio tool space
have been asking for for years,

00:08:17.430 --> 00:08:20.880
and I'm really pleased to see
that we're moving ahead with this.

00:08:21.100 --> 00:08:24.180
The goal here was to provide some
industrial strength foundation for

00:08:24.300 --> 00:08:26.800
your professional audio applications.

00:08:26.800 --> 00:08:29.000
And that starts at the hardware level.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:32.100
We are going to build,
provide a whole new hardware

00:08:32.100 --> 00:08:37.460
abstraction layer that's going to
provide low latency I/O for your cards.

00:08:37.950 --> 00:08:41.520
Hardware-based synchronization
for much better timing.

00:08:41.520 --> 00:08:45.100
True multi-channel in and outs,
so you can have, you know,

00:08:45.100 --> 00:08:48.830
eight parallel channels running
without having to bypass all the

00:08:48.860 --> 00:08:51.240
operating system to be able to do that.

00:08:51.630 --> 00:08:53.900
And we're going to also increase
the resolution of all the pipes.

00:08:54.090 --> 00:08:56.460
We'll be talking about
higher sampling rates,

00:08:56.600 --> 00:09:00.000
deeper bit resolutions,
as well as floating

00:09:00.400 --> 00:09:02.330
point processing pipes.

00:09:02.440 --> 00:09:07.080
And we'll also be adding a
plug-in architecture for effects.

00:09:07.400 --> 00:09:09.130
This is pretty good stuff.

00:09:09.130 --> 00:09:11.670
In the MIDI area,
we'll also be providing for the

00:09:11.800 --> 00:09:18.300
first time some standardized
low-level I/O managers for MIDI.

00:09:18.300 --> 00:09:21.300
We've never had this
standard on Mac OS 9.

00:09:21.300 --> 00:09:23.440
As you know,
most people end up relying on

00:09:23.440 --> 00:09:27.300
things like OMS or free MIDI.

00:09:27.300 --> 00:09:31.300
And on Mac OS X, we're going to provide
this basic infrastructure,

00:09:31.300 --> 00:09:34.070
and it'll provide the
I/O and the timing services.

00:09:34.390 --> 00:09:36.660
We're also making a significant
upgrade to the QuickTime music

00:09:36.790 --> 00:09:41.300
synthesizer to go along with these
new MIDI and sound capabilities.

00:09:41.300 --> 00:09:44.630
We're going to introduce a whole
new music synthesizer that plays

00:09:44.680 --> 00:09:47.240
MIDI files that's compatible with
the latest in MIDI standards,

00:09:47.380 --> 00:09:48.300
DLS2.

00:09:48.300 --> 00:09:52.090
And we'll have some new sequencing
APIs to make it easier and more

00:09:52.090 --> 00:09:55.300
powerful than ever to add sequence
music to your applications.

00:09:55.310 --> 00:09:57.260
And I hope you'll be happy.

00:09:57.330 --> 00:09:59.300
I think this stuff is in DP4.

00:09:59.300 --> 00:10:03.300
Some of this stuff is in DP4 now,
and we'll be seeding the remainder

00:10:03.300 --> 00:10:04.300
of it as the summer plays along.

00:10:04.300 --> 00:10:07.300
So, I hope this stuff plays out,
and I invite you to get involved.

00:10:07.300 --> 00:10:11.300
We've got three sessions at the show that
you should come and take a look at if

00:10:11.400 --> 00:10:13.300
you're interested in these technologies.

00:10:13.570 --> 00:10:15.290
And check it out.

00:10:16.820 --> 00:10:20.040
So, ProVideo.

00:10:20.290 --> 00:10:23.700
These days ProVideo is basically
about these three things.

00:10:23.700 --> 00:10:26.700
We're talking about
really high data rates,

00:10:26.710 --> 00:10:29.460
we're talking about being able to
handle multiple streams at once so

00:10:29.530 --> 00:10:33.140
you can create complex compositions,
and because these people,

00:10:33.170 --> 00:10:35.700
professionals are
concerned about their time,

00:10:35.770 --> 00:10:39.700
we're concerned about being able
to provide real-time capabilities.

00:10:39.900 --> 00:10:45.500
Apple has been working in partnership
with Matrox and Pinnacle to introduce two

00:10:45.500 --> 00:10:50.650
new very interesting hardware/software
combinations that you might have

00:10:50.800 --> 00:10:52.700
seen if you went to the NAB show.

00:10:52.870 --> 00:10:55.980
Since many of you probably weren't there,
I want to tell you a little

00:10:55.980 --> 00:10:57.590
bit about what we're doing.

00:10:57.810 --> 00:11:01.800
The first company that I want
to talk about is Pinnacle.

00:11:01.860 --> 00:11:04.190
They're introducing some
new hardware that's going to

00:11:04.190 --> 00:11:07.700
provide unbelievable prices.

00:11:07.770 --> 00:11:11.700
The capability to be able
to do HD format video.

00:11:11.700 --> 00:11:15.610
That's uncompressed,
high definition format video.

00:11:15.700 --> 00:11:21.670
This is data rates about 120,
130 megabytes per second on a Macintosh

00:11:21.670 --> 00:11:24.450
running with QuickTime and Final Cut.

00:11:24.860 --> 00:11:27.370
This is an amazing development.

00:11:27.760 --> 00:11:32.700
The monitor costs more than the
total cost of the rest of the system.

00:11:32.700 --> 00:11:36.290
It's a really wonderful development.

00:11:36.440 --> 00:11:40.440
We're also working with
Matrox on a very low cost,

00:11:40.440 --> 00:11:44.240
very powerful system to enable
you to do real-time effects,

00:11:44.250 --> 00:11:47.790
dual-stream processing of DV streams,
and standard definition

00:11:47.870 --> 00:11:49.320
uncompressed video.

00:11:49.400 --> 00:11:52.580
And I'd like to have Jim help
me show you a demonstration

00:11:52.700 --> 00:11:54.400
of what we're doing there.

00:11:54.440 --> 00:11:57.690
All this stuff is built on top of
the QuickTime effects architecture

00:11:57.690 --> 00:12:00.400
that's been in the system
for the last couple of years.

00:12:00.400 --> 00:12:03.470
And so if you want to take
advantage of these capabilities

00:12:03.470 --> 00:12:06.110
when the hardware starts shipping,
all you've got to do is support

00:12:06.110 --> 00:12:08.400
QuickTime and you'll be able to do this.

00:12:08.400 --> 00:12:12.340
Final Cut's calling the standard APIs,
and that's all it takes.

00:12:12.420 --> 00:12:14.400
Can we have a demo for it, please?

00:12:18.810 --> 00:12:22.000
Okay, so we're just running
a copy of Final Cut.

00:12:22.020 --> 00:12:24.700
We've got this Matrox card in the system.

00:12:24.700 --> 00:12:30.790
We've got a series of cut,
edit video clips.

00:12:35.180 --> 00:12:37.540
Now as you know,
Final Cut's got a very powerful

00:12:37.540 --> 00:12:40.260
capability for adding effects
and controlling effects

00:12:40.420 --> 00:12:44.100
rendering inside of the clips.

00:12:44.100 --> 00:12:47.100
I'm going to ask Jim to
add some dissolves.

00:12:47.100 --> 00:12:50.420
Normally when you do this,
you've got to now wait for a while

00:12:50.420 --> 00:12:52.100
while Final Cut renders this.

00:12:52.260 --> 00:12:55.320
But with the new hardware and
QuickTime's effects architecture,

00:12:55.640 --> 00:13:01.970
you just roll back to the top and play.

00:13:12.230 --> 00:13:14.220
So that's a pretty good effect.

00:13:14.470 --> 00:13:16.410
It's kind of the bread and
butter effect for editors.

00:13:16.530 --> 00:13:18.880
Do you have anything a little wackier?

00:13:20.850 --> 00:13:23.090
Two video tracks,
one called Lake Scene and the

00:13:23.110 --> 00:13:24.700
other one just Water Ripple.

00:13:24.730 --> 00:13:28.780
Water Ripple is just straight
on top of the Lake Scene,

00:13:28.790 --> 00:13:30.200
so you can't see the lake.

00:13:30.360 --> 00:13:34.040
But when we put this effect
on top of the Water Ripple,

00:13:34.040 --> 00:13:38.000
what's going to happen is the
Water Ripple frame is going to zoom in,

00:13:38.170 --> 00:13:41.530
spin around, and fly around a bit.

00:13:41.650 --> 00:13:44.660
And once again,
it's all green at the top,

00:13:44.820 --> 00:13:46.740
and this is all real time.

00:13:46.740 --> 00:13:50.650
So there's two DV streams in and one out.

00:13:50.900 --> 00:13:53.280
and of course,
just scrubbing right through.

00:13:53.310 --> 00:13:55.900
And you can even see the
transparency through that.

00:13:55.960 --> 00:13:56.900
Pretty cool.

00:13:56.920 --> 00:13:57.760
Pretty cool.

00:13:57.890 --> 00:13:59.900
Thank you.

00:13:59.900 --> 00:14:07.410
Now, can we go back to the slides,
please?

00:14:10.790 --> 00:14:14.850
So that was an example of using
QuickTime's creation environment,

00:14:14.860 --> 00:14:19.700
effects architecture, to do professional
quality video creation.

00:14:19.780 --> 00:14:22.640
Now, as you know,
Apple's been working real hard

00:14:22.640 --> 00:14:26.700
over the last year to make
consumer video creation a reality,

00:14:26.700 --> 00:14:31.170
and we've been working with a
lot of developers in other areas

00:14:31.170 --> 00:14:33.400
to drive that forward as well.

00:14:33.700 --> 00:14:36.670
QuickTime authoring being just
another part of QuickTime,

00:14:36.770 --> 00:14:40.630
it's not just a Macintosh feature,
it's something that we support on all

00:14:40.630 --> 00:14:42.700
the platforms where we take QuickTime.

00:14:42.900 --> 00:14:45.780
And this architecture was
designed in a scalable way,

00:14:45.780 --> 00:14:47.700
so it's not just something
that's going to be required

00:14:47.700 --> 00:14:49.590
or just used by professionals.

00:14:49.700 --> 00:14:55.140
Sony's created a very innovative product
that's based on QuickTime that they

00:14:55.140 --> 00:14:57.670
ship on all their VIO products now,
and we'd like to show you that.

00:14:57.700 --> 00:15:01.170
Leveraging many of the same
features that were used in the

00:15:01.170 --> 00:15:02.970
Matrox demo just a minute ago.

00:15:03.200 --> 00:15:04.700
Can we go back to the demo machine?

00:15:04.700 --> 00:15:06.950
Go to the laptop?

00:15:11.350 --> 00:15:15.840
This is an application
called Movie Shaker.

00:15:15.960 --> 00:15:18.960
So the first thing we need
to do is drop some media in,

00:15:18.980 --> 00:15:20.840
so we just reduce the screen size.

00:15:20.890 --> 00:15:24.090
Okay, here's a folder with just
some QuickTime movies.

00:15:24.370 --> 00:15:29.980
and it just drops right in and this
becomes content that we can use.

00:15:30.040 --> 00:15:31.390
And so we'll just pick one of these guys.

00:15:31.450 --> 00:15:35.460
Let's pick the road one because
he's pretty easy to see pretty well.

00:15:35.510 --> 00:15:37.580
And you have the play button.

00:15:37.690 --> 00:15:39.380
See, playing wrong.

00:15:39.550 --> 00:15:40.350
Scrub around.

00:15:40.490 --> 00:15:42.980
Normal QuickTime controller stuff,
movies.

00:15:43.040 --> 00:15:46.370
And take a look at some effects.

00:15:47.350 --> 00:15:50.400
And you have a preview mode
here that you can look at.

00:15:50.770 --> 00:15:51.760
Bubbles.

00:15:51.950 --> 00:15:53.700
It's all pretty cool,
because it's all Swift files.

00:15:53.700 --> 00:15:56.200
These are all flash animations.

00:15:56.430 --> 00:15:59.200
And then-- Obviously, in this context,
in the consumer context,

00:15:59.200 --> 00:16:04.120
the goal is not so much workflow and
process and speed and stuff like that.

00:16:04.220 --> 00:16:06.700
It's more about fun and creativity.

00:16:06.700 --> 00:16:10.700
And we just play through,
and there's the result.

00:16:11.020 --> 00:16:14.200
Just right away.

00:16:14.300 --> 00:16:16.820
And we can also do some text.

00:16:20.560 --> 00:16:23.170
The canonical text that you always had.

00:16:23.170 --> 00:16:24.800
And you can get a couple previews.

