00:18:35.620 --> 00:18:39.500
The first thing we need to do is talk a
little bit about what is interactivity.

00:18:39.500 --> 00:18:44.020
The basic concept here is we've
got a really powerful engine for

00:18:44.020 --> 00:18:48.500
creating kind of linear media assets,
video, audio, whatever.

00:18:48.500 --> 00:18:53.880
We've also built into QuickTime some very
powerful features to be able to allow

00:18:54.010 --> 00:18:58.940
you to customize both the appearance
and the behavior of your media.

00:18:59.590 --> 00:19:02.640
Other people are doing things with skins,
which is really not the same thing.

00:19:02.640 --> 00:19:06.370
That's about taking an application and
changing the way the application looks,

00:19:06.370 --> 00:19:08.630
but it really isn't
responsive to the media,

00:19:08.820 --> 00:19:12.500
and it's not able to modify the
overall behavior of the application.

00:19:12.560 --> 00:19:14.410
We think this is really important.

00:19:14.410 --> 00:19:17.340
We think that the thing ought
to be to skin the media,

00:19:17.340 --> 00:19:18.490
not the players.

00:19:18.500 --> 00:19:21.500
So we've built some pretty cool
technologies to allow you to do that,

00:19:21.500 --> 00:19:25.500
and there are a number of
ways you can access this.

00:19:25.510 --> 00:19:27.500
The first one is through
the movie controller.

00:19:27.500 --> 00:19:29.580
If you're programming
with QuickTime today,

00:19:29.580 --> 00:19:32.620
you know that the movie controller is
responsible for all the interaction

00:19:33.010 --> 00:19:34.290
that takes place in the movie.

00:19:34.500 --> 00:19:37.040
And there's a lot of interesting
things you can do with that,

00:19:37.240 --> 00:19:40.490
although most of that stuff's probably
not obvious if you're not a programmer.

00:19:40.500 --> 00:19:43.510
We've also built this very
powerful infrastructure inside of

00:19:43.540 --> 00:19:45.470
QuickTime that we call Wired Movies.

00:19:45.530 --> 00:19:49.870
It's basically the capability
to execute code inside the

00:19:49.870 --> 00:19:52.280
context of the movie playback.

00:19:52.690 --> 00:19:55.500
And this is code which
is sort of like Java.

00:19:55.500 --> 00:19:56.500
It's portable.

00:19:56.500 --> 00:19:58.420
It's not tied to a specific
machine architecture.

00:19:58.500 --> 00:20:01.590
And it has the capability to communicate
with other parts of QuickTime,

00:20:01.590 --> 00:20:04.940
to be able to send events,
and be able to modify behavior based

00:20:05.060 --> 00:20:09.500
upon user input and other events or
conditions that arise in the movie.

00:20:09.570 --> 00:20:12.700
We've also built an incredibly
comprehensive set of interfaces

00:20:12.990 --> 00:20:14.500
to QuickTime from Java.

00:20:14.500 --> 00:20:17.500
So if you're a Java programmer and
you like to work in that environment,

00:20:17.670 --> 00:20:20.460
you can do pretty much everything
you can do with QuickTime,

00:20:20.530 --> 00:20:23.500
the C APIs, plus some other things.

00:20:23.500 --> 00:20:24.500
