00:25:58.590 --> 00:26:02.190
So now I want to talk about
QuickTime and servers.

00:26:03.230 --> 00:26:06.680
This is an area that's been
relatively new to the QuickTime team.

00:26:06.900 --> 00:26:12.000
We've been working with server-based
technologies basically since we

00:26:12.090 --> 00:26:14.090
started doing the live streaming stuff.

00:26:14.100 --> 00:26:17.100
Now the first question is,
why do we care?

00:26:17.100 --> 00:26:18.050
What are servers good for?

00:26:18.090 --> 00:26:20.480
When we thought about this,
we came up with, say,

00:26:20.530 --> 00:26:24.810
a half a dozen basic things that servers
do really well that are very hard

00:26:24.960 --> 00:26:27.100
to do from the client all by itself.

00:26:27.340 --> 00:26:28.110
Access control.

00:26:28.110 --> 00:26:31.370
If you've got valuable assets
sitting on a server somewhere,

00:26:31.380 --> 00:26:34.730
you don't want to just hand them
over to the client and let them

00:26:34.730 --> 00:26:39.040
be distributed anywhere without
any control around the internet.

00:26:39.100 --> 00:26:42.000
Servers are great at
providing access control.

00:26:42.280 --> 00:26:44.100
They're also great for copy protection.

00:26:44.100 --> 00:26:47.260
That means you can take your clips
and potentially encrypt them,

00:26:47.260 --> 00:26:48.070
encode them.

00:26:48.160 --> 00:26:53.140
You have a tight coupling between the
server and the client so that only this

00:26:53.140 --> 00:26:56.100
customized client can access the media.

00:26:56.100 --> 00:26:57.990
Servers, of course,
are great at counting.

00:26:58.090 --> 00:26:59.770
If you've got a lot of
people hitting the server,

00:26:59.770 --> 00:27:03.210
accessing various kinds of media,
the servers tend to do a much

00:27:03.450 --> 00:27:06.740
better job than a client of finding
out what's going on with all the

00:27:06.740 --> 00:27:08.090
various clients in the world.

00:27:08.100 --> 00:27:12.410
Servers also have some powerful
capabilities for looking

00:27:12.410 --> 00:27:17.020
at the environment around
them and producing dynamic,

00:27:17.020 --> 00:27:19.930
just-in-time media compositions.

00:27:20.100 --> 00:27:22.910
And then, of course,
servers have always been kind of a

00:27:22.910 --> 00:27:25.100
hub for community kinds of activities.

00:27:25.100 --> 00:27:30.100
Whether that's, you know,
email servers or things like that.

00:27:30.100 --> 00:27:33.030
And then, servers are big databases.

00:27:33.100 --> 00:27:37.060
These are really important concepts
when you start to think about what

00:27:37.150 --> 00:27:38.940
do servers mean for QuickTime.

00:27:39.100 --> 00:27:42.340
Now,
the way the servers end up interacting

00:27:42.340 --> 00:27:44.880
with QuickTime is really simple.

00:27:45.100 --> 00:27:51.670
The whole mechanism ends up basically
being embedded in the communication that

00:27:51.670 --> 00:27:54.100
goes between the client and the server.

00:27:54.100 --> 00:27:58.070
In simple transactions relating to URLs.

00:27:58.100 --> 00:28:01.740
The client requests the URL,
the server interprets the

00:28:01.860 --> 00:28:04.100
URL and responds accordingly.

00:28:04.120 --> 00:28:08.100
So depending on what you
decide to put in the URL,

00:28:08.100 --> 00:28:11.030
you can drive all kinds of
different sorts of behavior.

00:28:11.100 --> 00:28:13.090
This is old hat for the server guys.

00:28:13.280 --> 00:28:16.320
But it's an incredibly simple
concept that has incredibly

00:28:16.550 --> 00:28:18.010
powerful ramifications.

00:28:18.100 --> 00:28:22.090
So with QuickTime today,
there's basically two

00:28:22.090 --> 00:28:23.890
ways you can approach...

00:28:24.420 --> 00:28:28.690
Customizing the behavior of
QuickTime through the server.

00:28:28.690 --> 00:28:31.830
One of them is one we've
recently introduced.

00:28:32.040 --> 00:28:34.060
That's QuickTime streaming
server plug-ins.

00:28:34.090 --> 00:28:37.800
There's a very rich set of
plug-in capabilities for servers,

00:28:37.810 --> 00:28:41.740
for the QuickTime streaming server that
will allow you to access accounting

00:28:41.740 --> 00:28:46.560
and logging kinds of functionalities,
being able to pre-process streams,

00:28:46.720 --> 00:28:50.570
being able to control access
to the back-end data access

00:28:50.570 --> 00:28:51.960
portion of the server.

00:28:51.960 --> 00:28:52.940
It's incredibly powerful.

00:28:52.970 --> 00:28:55.380
There's a whole session about
this that you should go to and

00:28:55.560 --> 00:28:56.690
check out if you're interested.

00:28:56.940 --> 00:28:59.000
And then of course
there's CGI programming,

00:28:59.090 --> 00:29:02.110
which is sort of the die-hard
of server-side programming,

00:29:02.220 --> 00:29:03.680
client-server interactions.

00:29:03.740 --> 00:29:08.640
And this is basically custom applications
that masquerade as web servers.

00:29:08.690 --> 00:29:10.780
And WebObjects is a
great example of that.

00:29:10.830 --> 00:29:15.770
And I guess now that Apple's
handing that out for dirt cheap,

00:29:16.060 --> 00:29:17.780
you should get a copy and
see what you can do with it.

00:29:17.780 --> 00:29:20.230
It's really, really powerful.

00:29:20.870 --> 00:29:25.410
The servers basically interact with
the client by passing back media.

00:29:25.890 --> 00:29:28.180
We process movies, of course.

00:29:28.330 --> 00:29:31.420
We can also receive any media
that QuickTime knows how to open,

00:29:31.480 --> 00:29:33.690
so it doesn't have to be a .mov file.

00:29:33.700 --> 00:29:35.700
It doesn't have to be a
QuickTime movie per se.

00:29:35.700 --> 00:29:37.190
It can be anything that we can open.

00:29:37.510 --> 00:29:41.950
And we also support SMILE,
